40|$|This paper studies how {{exogenous}} tax changes affect {{credit market}} {{conditions in the}} US and UK. Using both structural VAR and structural factor-augmented VAR (FAVAR) model, we find that tax-policy shocks have significant effects on the <b>credit</b> <b>spread.</b> Specifically, the <b>credit</b> <b>spread</b> responds first positively and then negatively to an exogenous tax increase in the two countries. Moreover, the impulse responses of the <b>credit</b> <b>spread</b> to tax-policy shocks do not always accord well with the impulse responses of the output. This indicates that there are channels of tax policy transmission to the <b>credit</b> <b>spread</b> other than through {{its impact on the}} business cycle...|$|R
